Biases  Against  Women and  People of  Color 	  Dr. Ochoa is one of just a few dozen female astronauts in the U.S. She is also the first Hispanic woman in the world to go into space. Although females make up more than half of the U.S. population, fewer than 25 percent of U.S. astronauts are women. Women are also under-represented in science, especially physical sciences such as chemistry and physics. What explains this? Throughout history, women—and also people of color of both genders—have rarely had the same chances as white males for education and careers in science. Cultural, social, and economic biases have made it far harder for them than for white males to excel in this area. This explains why there have been fewer scientists among their ranks. 
