Saturated vs.  Unsaturated  Solutions 	  The maximum amount of sugar that will dissolve in a liter of 20 °C water is 2000 grams. A sugar-water solution that contains 1 liter of water and 2000 grams of sugar is said to be saturated. A saturated solution is a solution that contains as much solute as can dissolve in a given solvent at a given temperature. If you add more than 2000 grams of sugar to a liter of 20 °C water, the extra sugar won’t dissolve. On the other hand, a solution containing less than a given temperature is called an unsaturated solution. You can learn more about saturated and unsaturated solutions by watching the video at this URL: URL . 
